<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>THE BUSINESS, INNOVATION AND SKILLS COMMITTEE INQUIRY INTO THE EXTRACTIVE INDUSTRIES SECTOR</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:20pt">EIS 18</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Confederation of UK Coal Producers (COALPRO)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Background</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">onfederation of UK Coal Producers (Coalpro)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> represents the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">coal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> ind</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ustry within the United Kingdom, our members produce 95% of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">coal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> mined in the UK from both deep and surface mines</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Coal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Industry</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> produced 16.3Mt in 2012 around 90% of which was sold into power stations in the UK.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Coalpro is a member of the CBI M</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">inerals Group.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">These sales would otherwise be replaced by imported coal as almost 50Mt was consumed by UK power stations in 2012. The industry employed just over 6,000 people to produce this output and although this has declined in 2013 following the closu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">re of Maltby Colliery and Daw Mill Colliery and the collapse of two of the companies operating surface mines in Scotland we expect the figure to be well in excess of 4,500 direct employees by the early part of 2014 as some the operations in Scotland re-com</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mence production. In addition to the power station market coal is an essential and affordable fuel for households which are off the gas grid (estimated to be 6 million homes) and of course is used by some key industries such as cement and sugar processing.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">One industry which has to use coal is steel-making as the carbon in the coal and the iron ore chemically bond in the blast furnace, in this case there is no alternative fuel and although the majority of the coal used in this process in the UK is imported</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> there are some coals which are suitable in parts of the UK, notably North-East England and South Wales. Tata steel have a policy of preferring to purchase these coals when they are available, as they provide secure and local supplies with reduced costs of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> transportation both in fuel and emissions. The suitability depends on the characteristics of each individual coal seam in the mine and the mine must have other markets for the other coal seams it mines (principally power generation).   </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Executive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Summary</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In its heyday, the UK underground coal industry was a key driver in providing the skills base for the extractive industries but with its now virtual demise the number of mining and related training courses has dwindled to very few</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, however, equipment manuf</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">acturers and mining engineers from the UK are still highly regarded and can be found in key positions in countries such as Australia, India and South Africa.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">   </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he level of engagement with NGOs and communities in the UK is excellent at both a local and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">national level.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The industry makes an important contribution to biodiversity through the restoration of surface coal mine sites.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">here has been no dialogue /consultation to date with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the UK mining companies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">who operate within the UK about the s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cope and imp</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lementation of EITI.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The ability of deep mines to compete in the global coal mining sector will be seriously hampered if they are not allowed to claim relief from the effects of the EMR package as an EII.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UK government should champion an Energy Policy whic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">h maintains coal-fired generation plant in the portfolio until the fleet is de-carbonised with the introduction of CCS and facilitates</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> indigenous </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">coal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> extraction </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as the main source of supply. This will ensure that there is sufficient competition and that t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he most affordable fuel is maintained during the new build of low carbon technologies. Reliance on gas as the only fossil fuel in the mix is high risk on price, availability and locks in carbon beyond 2030 if new gas stations have to be built to satisfy de</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mand.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Questions</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.59pt; padding-left:5.41pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What is the contribution to the UK economy of extractive industries in the UK?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Coal mining in the UK contributes both financially and socially on a national and local level. Coal deposits are present in some of the more economically deprived areas of Scotland , Northern England and South Wales and the mines, whether surface or underg</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">round,  predominantly employ local labour. The cost of regenerating these areas after deep mine closure both in social and economic terms is well known to Government. In addition, local haulage and small engineering businesses depend on the coal mines, bot</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">h surface and underground, for a large proportion of their turnover. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A large proportion of rail freight traffic is from the transport of bulk materials, c35% in 2010 of all freight was the haulage of coal to power stations, UK produced coal accounts for a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bout one third of this total. Track access fees for these movements make up a significant portion of Network Rail’s income.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Case Study </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Kier Minerals Ltd Greenburn Surface Coal Mine</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Kier Minerals Ltd (part of Kier Group Plc)   currently own and operate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> a surface coal mine in the UK, the Greenburn Surface Mine, near New Cumnock in East Ayrshire. Reserves exist to continue until 2022.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">At the end of August 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> site has produced 5,492,000 tonnes of coal supplying English power stations by rail and cont</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ributing to an indigenous solution to UK energy security.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The Greenburn operation currently employs 151 hourly paid individuals and additionally 48 sub-contractors are permanently employed giving a total of 199. Of this total 84 live within 10 miles of th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">e site and 116 live within a 15 mile radius. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Based on the above employment figures and using Scottish Government published multipliers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> a further 160 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">indirect jobs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> (plant hire</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">haulage eq</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">uipment repair etc) are created</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">and a further 234 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">induced jobs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">jo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">bs supported by direct and i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ndirect employees spending wage</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:2.25pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Source:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">(</span><a href="http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/Statistics/Browse/Economy/Input-Output/Downloads/IO1998-2009latest"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/Statistics/Browse/Economy/Input-Outpu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">t/Downloads/IO1998-2009latest</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">These figure are in the context of sign</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ificant unemployment of 10.9% (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">April 2012 to March 2013)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> for East Ayrshire </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">which rises to 11.9% when considering males only</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">, who are typically </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">employed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> in mining</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">. The wage bill in the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> last financial year was £5.73 million</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> the majority going into the local commun</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ity within 15 miles of the site</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> Source:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">(</span><a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/reports/lmp/la/2038432129/report.aspx"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/reports/lmp/la/2038432129/report.aspx</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><a href="http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/index.html"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/index.html</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Kier have also contributed £1.54 million (end August 2013) into the local community trust which p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">rovides funding to local community projects and will continue to contribute on future production.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Kier Group plc has established a Non-Vocational Qualification (NVQ) Centre at Greenburn. To date the Centre has completed 116 vocational qualifications in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">level 2 Plant Operations plus 6 supervisors achieving level 3 awards. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Further Example</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">UK Coal Production Ltd operates a surface coal mine called Potland Burn near Ashington in Northumberland. The site commenced operations in 2010 and will extract 2.2 mi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">llion tonnes of coal over its five year life</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">, in 2012 the site employed 96 people of whom 82% live within 15 miles of the site. As part of a signed Legal Agreement the company has contributed £500,000 into a local community fund which is used to promote co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">mmunity benefits and amenities. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">All the coal from site is transported by rail to English Power Stations and has a much lower Carbon Footprint from both excavation and delivery than imported coal.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.74pt; padding-left:5.26pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How does the UK based extractive industries support </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">employment a) in the UK and b) for UK citizens overseas?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The indigenous </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">coal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> industry</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in the UK provides high quality jobs in rural or deprived areas, both directly employed in the mining operations but also in the supply chain and in particular the speci</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">alist equipment and plant required, and the maintenance and small engineering and repair sector. The coal industry employed over 6,000 people in 2012 and despite the closure of Maltby and Daw Mill Collieries in 2013 and the suspension of operations at the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">majority of sites in Scotland there are 4,100 employees at the end of August 2013 which we expect to increase to in excess of 4,500 during the next six months as operations in Scotland re-start. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Supply chain jobs dependent on the coal mining sector are a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">round 15,000.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Mining consultants from UK based organisations are busy on coal and other mineral projects worldwide and particularly in India currently. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.74pt; padding-left:5.26pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Does UK industry benefit more widely from the UK’s position as a centre for extractive industries </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">i.e. in sales of machinery and services to international businesses in the sector?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Consultancy services from the UK on mining projects are in high demand, and the fact that they are familiar with UK coal underground systems gives the competitive advan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tage that the deep reserves worked here give unique experience, compared with some other coal deposits worldwide.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UK manufacturers were involved at the start of the mechanisation programme which changed the face of underground coal production in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1960’s and 1970’s. The continuing development and improvements made to this equipment as reserves became deeper again enhances the design and supply reputation of UK based companies.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.74pt; padding-left:5.26pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Has the boom in London-listed extractive companies with businesses over</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">seas over the last two decades resulted in a strengthening in the UK’s competitive position in this sector?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In the coal sector</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> UK operations are all performed by UK based companies and very few have overseas interests. The presence of large mining compan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ies in London offices does not encourage them to use UK based suppliers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and most mining equipment supply is now done by large global corporations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, notwithstanding that, the engineering design for these products is maintained in the UK but some of the manu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">facturing has moved to China and USA.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.74pt; padding-left:5.26pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What are the corporate governance concerns raised by the number of extractive industries companies listed in the UK? Are there reputational risks for the UK and UK financial institutions in being a centre for such bus</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">inesses?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oalpro has no relevant information to enable it to make comment on this question.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.74pt; padding-left:5.26pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Is there sufficient engagement between UK extractive industries and the NGO sector? Are there examples of best practice in engagement between the extractive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">industries and NGOs?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We believe the level of engagement with NGOs and communities in the UK is excellent at both a local and national level. Examples of the engagement are set out below:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">National Engagement - The UK Minerals Forum</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The UK Minerals Forum was set </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">up </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by the CBI Minerals Group in 2006 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(of which Coalpro is a member) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">because there was </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a perceived n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eed to draw together all key stak</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eholders, to debate and inform G</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">overnment and the public on the prudent use, sustainable management and supply of UK minerals. The UKMF has a broad membership drawn from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">industry, regulators, NGOs and G</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">overnment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> who sit as observers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. It holds regular meetings and convenes working groups </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to research and report on critical issues. We believe the Forum is a good example of best practice in engagement between </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">all stakeholders who</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> have an interest in the UK based extractive industry</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:9.5pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:9.5pt">Forum is submitting its own evidence to the Committee a</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:9.5pt">nd further details can be viewed at: </span><a href="http://www.bgs.ac.uk/ukmf/home.html"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.bgs.ac.uk/ukmf/home.html</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:9.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Local E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">ngagement</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Engagement with local communities is enshrined within the land use planning legis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lation and the coal industry </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">has for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> many years worked hard to be part or the local community rather</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> than</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> apart from it.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> In all cases the surface mined coal sites set up a Community Fund of which the local liaison group and the Parish Council decide the most appropriate use for the co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mmunity adjacent to or affected by the mining operation.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Site specific liaison groups normally include representatives of local residents, local elected officials and locally based NGOs. Further details on the statutory obligation to engage with local comm</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">unities can be viewed at:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/policies/giving-communities-more-power-in-planning-local-development"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/government/policies/giving-communities-more-power-in-planning-local-development</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:none">During any p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:none">lanning application and during site operations the mining companies work with bodies such as English Nature, English Heritage, RSPB, SEPA and Natural Resources Wales.</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.74pt; padding-left:5.26pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Does the UK have the skills base to remain a centre for the extractive industries and to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> ensure that UK based businesses benefit from potential future opportunities such as shale gas?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">After recent changes in both the deep mine and surface mine portfolio in England and Scotland, UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> listed extractive companies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> operations in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">do not have coal mining interests outside these shores. The large London listed mining companies have no operations in the UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and thus have limited </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">incentive to support the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> UK skills base. In its heyday</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the UK underground coal industry was a key driver in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> providing the skills base for the extractive industries</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> but with its now virtual demise the number of mining and related</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> training</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> course</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has dwindled to very few. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Undergraduate degrees in Mining Engineering were offered at a number of Universities as re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cently as 20 years ago and graduates found employment worldwide.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ack of a large</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> indigenous industry</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> also</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> means there is reduced opportunity for students to gain practical experience or interest </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mining operations. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The  recruitment of new Managers </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">into the UK coal industry is difficult, and the path that formerly existed of gaining practical experience in the UK and then using those skills worldwide has disappeared. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The main mining relate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d courses are now restricted to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">very few universities, such</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as Camborne School of Mines, part of the Exeter University and course</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> provided by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">erby and Northumbria Universities  </span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 61.25pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><a href="http://emps.exeter.ac.uk/csm/"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://emps.exeter.ac.uk/csm/</span></a></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 60.65pt; padding-left:7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><a href="http://www.northumbria.ac.uk/?view=CourseDetail&amp;code=DTPSUM6"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.northumbria.ac.uk/?view=CourseDetail&amp;code=DTPSUM6</span></a></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 60.65pt; padding-left:7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><a href="http://www.derby.ac.uk/courses/udc/minerals-management-bsc-hons/"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.derby.ac.uk/courses/udc/minerals-management-bsc-hons/</span></a></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.74pt; padding-left:5.26pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What is the impact of the indu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">stry of the UK signing up to the EITI?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">So far as Coalpro is aware there has been no contact to involve coal mining companies in discussion of the possibility of signing up to the EITI.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The regulatory framework in the UK currently ensures that all payments made to local and central movement in the form of fees, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">business rates and other </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">taxes and contributions to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">local infrastructure is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> done so in a fully transparent way</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and the Group bel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ieves that there is no requirement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> further regulation.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is noted from the press release dated 10</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> July 2013 posted on the EITI website that Business Minister Jo Swinson said </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">…..“Under the EITI, extractives companies operating in the UK would report</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> material payments to the UK government, totalling billions of pounds, who will also report the receipts it received. The payments of tax, licence fees and other receipts will be disclosed in reports conforming to the EITI standards</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We seek urgent dialo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">gue on the status of UK based extraction under EITI.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.74pt; padding-left:5.26pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Would increased regulation for London listed extractives companies result in competition from elsewhere or can it be used to make the UK a centre of excellence for best practice and corporate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">governance?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Government should be aware that London listed extractive companies currently have global offices and operations, they might view any attempt by the UK to impose further regulation as restrictive and decide to centre their businesses elsewhere.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.81pt; padding-left:0.19pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What is the competitive landscape for the extractive industries in the 21st Century and is it in the UK’s interest to remain a global centre for them?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">If we wish to keep the core skills in coal mining and maintain our reputation as some of the best Mini</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ng Engineers at depth or the most efficient truck and shovel method surface miners then an Energy Policy has to be developed that allows coal-fired power stations to continue in operation until 2030. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We believe there is too much focus on the short term i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n Government. There are long lead times, often </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">at least </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ten years, to bring new mineral extraction operation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on stream. They cannot be switched on</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and off,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and once </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lost</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, the industry and its support infrastructure will be very difficult to get back.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Ener</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">gy minerals are vital to the UK’s energy intensive industries’ competitive position, the recent publicity around shale gas has led to the Government saying that indigenous resources help to insulate us from supply shortages and price volatility but the sam</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e thinking does not seem to apply to coal.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We know that all fossil fuels require Carbon Capture and Storage as soon as practicable and are frustrated by the fact that it is now seven years since the UK’s first CCS competition was launched and so far we ha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ve not commenced any physical construction works and have spent very little of the promised £1bn for full scale demonstration of CCS.</span></p><p